ale":"1542–Afdød","1574–1644":"1574–1644","1538–1604":"1538–1604","1644":"1644","1542":"1542","1574":"1574","13 April 1574":"13. april 1574","2 April 1604":"2. april 1604","1538":"1538","1604":"1604","Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Salisbury St Martin, Wiltshire, England":"Salisbury St Martin, Wiltshire, England"},"nl":{"1538–2 April 1604":"1538–2 april 1604","1542–Female":"1542–Overleden","1574–1644":"1574–1644","1538–1604":"1538–1604","1644":"1644","1542":"1542","1574":"1574","13 April 1574":"13 april 1574","2 April 1604":"2 april 1604","1538":"1538","1604":"1604","Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Salisbury St Martin, Wiltshire, England":"Salisbury St Martin, Wiltshire, England"},"en":{"1538–2 April 1604":"1538–2 April 1604","1542–Female":"1542–Deceased","1574–1644":"1574–1644","1538–1604":"1538–1604","1644":"1644","1542":"1542","1574":"1574","13 April 1574":"13 April 1574","2 April 1604":"2 April 1604","1538":"1538","1604":"1604","Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Salisbury St Martin, Wiltshire, England":"Salisbury St Martin, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Heath","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(on the) heath’ (Middle English <i>he(a)th</i>, Old English <i>hǣth</i>) or else a habitational name from any of numerous places called with this word. The same word also denoted heather, the characteristic plant of heathland areas. This surname has also been established in Dublin, Ireland, since the late 16th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Haith","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and East Yorkshire): variant of   Heath  ."]},{"name":"Heathman","meanings":["English: topographic name denoting a dweller ‘on the heath’, from Middle English <i>he(a)th</i> + <i>man(ne)</i>. Compare   Heath   and   Heather  ."]},{"name":"Hatton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Hatton (Cheshire, Derbyshire, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Shropshire, Staffordshire, Warwickshire), Hatton Hall (Cheshire), or Cold and High Hatton (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Heath  .","English: variant of <b>Atton</b> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>). Compare   Towne  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Chatáin</b>, a patronymic from a personal name meaning ‘servant of (Saint) Catan’; see   McHatton  ."]},{"name":"Heather","meanings":["English: topographic name denoting a ‘dweller on the heath’, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>hethe</i>; compare   Heath  . The name may also be habitational name from Heather (Leicestershire), from Old English <i>hǣthor</i> ‘heathland’ (<i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + the noun suffix <i>-or</i>) or <i>hǣddre</i> ‘heather’. This surname is widespread in southern England, and also established in Ireland."]},{"name":"Health","meanings":["(1997: 105;2010: NA)","Altered form of English and Scottish   Heath  .","English and Scottish: perhaps a nickname from the vocabulary word <i>health</i>. — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is 105."]},{"name":"Hoad","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived on a heath, from Middle English <i>hoth</i> ‘heath’ (Old English <i>hāth</i>, a byform of Old English <i>hǣth</i>), or a habitational name from a place so named, such as Hoath in Kent. This form was restricted in the Middle Ages to southeastern England, and the surname is still largely confined to Kent, Surrey, and Sussex. Compare   Heath  ."]},{"name":"Heid","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Eckhart, Gerd, Gotthilf, Heinz, Klaus, Konrad, Kurt, Manfred, Ralf, Uli.","German, Swiss German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): topographic name from Middle High German <i>heide</i>, German <i>Heide</i> ‘heath, moor, open, uncultivated land’. Compare   Heath  .","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Haido</i>, a short form of any of various compound names beginning with <i>haid</i> ‘heath’ (i.e. wasteland, often with heather)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Heath was born in 1538, in Kent, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Anna Poyser. He died on 2 April 1604, in his hometown, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1538–2 April 1604":"1538–2. aprill 1604","1542–Female":"1542–Surnud","1574–1644":"1574–1644","1538–1604":"1538–1604","1644":"1644","1542":"1542","1574":"1574","13 April 1574":"13. aprill 1574","2 April 1604":"2. aprill 1604","1538":"1538","1604":"1604","Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Salisbury St Martin, Wiltshire, England":"Salisbury St Martin, Wiltshire, England"},"fi":{"1538–2